[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Dunbar is an 85-year-old woman from San Jose, California who has sought care at SGSHH multiple times in the past.  She presented for evaluation of a right lower quadrant mass and had an open right hemicolectomy on 10/18/10 with excision of invasive adenocarcinoma of the cecum.
#1 Invasive adenocarcinoma of the cecum, negative lymph nodes, s/p open right hemicolectomy on 10/18/10
Mrs. Dunbar presented for evaluation with RUQ and right flank pain, decreased appetite and weight-loss and a CT demonstrating a right lower quadrant right flank mass that could not be differentiated from the cecum.  Surgery included removal of a small portion of distal ileum.  She tolerated the procedure well and post-operative course was complicated by ileus requiring placement of an NG tube and acute kidney injury.  Her baseline creatinine is 0.8 and peaked at 2.4 on 10/22/10.  BUN high was 31.  There was no UA performed in the post-operative period.  She was receiving about 1.6L IV fluids daily in the days prior to the creatinine peak.  She does not recall having a bowel movement post-operatively (she does recall passing gas).  Multiple bowel movements are charted.  She was noted to be deconditioned following the surgery and transferred to LGCH for continuing rehabilitation with the plan of returning to independent living alone at her home in San Jose, California.  Presently she is feeling okay, noting that she has abdominal pain most prominent in the RLQ.  She is disappointed that her daughter has taken all her clothes home with her to the Saint John, Washington during the hospitalization so that here at LGCH she has only one outfit in which to dress for meals and ambulation.  She is also missing her husband who died five years ago.
#2 Coccygeal pressure ulcer, stage 2
This was noted to be present at her outpatient clinic appointments prior to the surgery and hospitalization.  It appears to have improved from purple and non-blanchable to red and blanchable.  A candidal-appearing perineal infection was also noted.  She received wound care while hospitalized and comes with recommendations for wound care including Nystatin powder, dressing changes, repositioning, limited head of bed elevation and a Roho cushion.

[end section id="20103"]

[start section id="20107"]

MEDICAL HISTORY
1. Cholangitis following cholecystectomy in 1980s, complicated by hepatic abscess and resulting in numerous surgeries including hepaticojejunostomy and placement of a percutaneous biliary catheter which was removed recently after being in place 11 years, chronic antibiotic prophylaxis using Cefadroxil
2. History of diverticulitis
3. Asthma
4. History of cutaneous sarcoidosis
5. Type II diabetes mellitus, adult-onset, using insulin
6. Chest pain syndrome, thought to have a vasospastic component
7. Hypothyroidism
SURGICAL HISTORY
1. See #1 above, cholecystectomy in 1980s
2. Tonsillectomy
3. Appendectomy
4. TAH for menorrhagia and fibroids

